{
  "doc_id": "44435",
  "text": "The electrochemical sensors, commonly referred to as \"electrodes\", are ideal candidates as they can be fabricated with low-cost to detect Pb with higher precision and accuracy. The material system of a sensing electrode is the key ingredient in maximizing overall performance of an electrochemical analysis instrument. Specifically, electrode materials based on carbon nanomaterials, [CITATION_1] metal nanoparticles, [CITATION_2] and a number of selectivity-enhancing polymeric or organic materials [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] have attracted tremendous research interest for their collective attributes such as high effective surface area, enhanced electron transfer, ability to be miniaturized, and improved selectivity. More notably, nanomaterials based electrodes made up of easily available electrode materials by a facile and scalable 4 synthesis method can be exploited to fabricate low cost electrodes for the analysis of multiple environmental targets such as heavy metals such as lead and pharmaceutical contaminants such as acetaminophen and estrogen in drinking water. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] The ability to detect multiple environmental targets at low cost and in an easy to use manner requires careful selection of sensing materials to provide high sensitivity and selectivity, development of simple modification approaches and user-friendly analysis steps.",
